article.description:
Jalen Rose capped a career-high 44-point performance by hitting a 15-foot jump shot as the buzzer sounded
Saturday night, giving Chicago a 114-112 double-overtime victory over the Houston Rockets and snapping the Bulls' eight-game losing streak.

related.description:
Houston Rockets guard Steve Francis missed
Saturday's game with the Chicago Bulls after complaining of
migraine headaches.

article.headline: Rose a thorn in side of Rockets
article.linkText: Rose scores 44 in Bulls' double-OT win vs. Rockets
article.story:
HOUSTON (AP) -- Jalen Rose was ready to redeem himself for missing a recent game-winning opportunity. In the second overtime, he got that chance.
Rose

Rose capped a career-high 44-point performance by making a 15-footer at the buzzer in double overtime to give the Chicago Bulls a 114-112 victory over the Houston Rockets on Saturday night. The shot snapped Chicago's eight-game losing streak. "This was an old-school shootout. I welcomed the opportunity and the pressure," Rose said. "I was disappointed because in Sacramento few games ago I had the opportunity to win the game and I didn't come through." Rose hit a jumper at the buzzer in the first overtime, then scored six of the Bulls' eight points in the second overtime. A pair of baskets by Kenny Thomas gave the Rockets a 110-106 lead. The Bulls then scored six straight to lead 112-110 with 48 seconds left. A basket by Cuttino Mobley tied the score with 20 seconds left and set up Rose's game-winning shot. Chicago coach Bill Cartwright was pleased with his team's intensity. "I think that our guys hung in there great with the eight-game losing streak. They could have quit at any time, but they kept fighting," Cartwright said. Chicago's Charles Oakley was less complimentary. "I'm just glad to get this win and get out of here. This is two teams going nowhere. It was the battle of the bottom," Oakley said. Moochie Norris recorded a career-high 17 assists, the most by a Rocket since Kenny Smith had 17 against the Lakers in 1992. Mobley led Houston with 37 points, followed by Thomas with 24 and Kelvin Cato with 15. "It was a well-fought game. We were fighting for our lives. I felt we had some opportunities to close the game out and didn't. That happens because you get fatigued when the game goes on that long," Norris said. Marcus Fizer had 20 points for Chicago, while Travis Best added 14. With the score tied 102-102 and 40 seconds left in the first overtime, Rose found Trenton Hassell underneath for a 104-102 lead. A 3-point shot by Norris and a free throw by Thomas gave Houston a 106-104 advantage. Best then hit a jump shot from the corner as the buzzer sounded to send the game into double overtime. Mobley scored 14 points in the first eight minutes of the fourth period to spark Houston to a 93-88 lead with 4:02 left. Rose countered with seven straight points to give the Bulls a 95-93 advantage with 1:42 reamining. After a 3-point play by Norris, Rose connected on two free throws, giving him 19 fourth-period points and the Bulls a 97-96 lead. A basket by Mobley with 32 seconds left and a free throw by Fizer with eight seconds remaining left the game tied 98-98 at the end of regulation. Game notes
Steve Francis did not play after complaining of migraine headaches ... Francis is the only player in the NBA to average 20 points, six assists and six rebounds per game. Houston is 2-21 in the 23 games missed by Francis this season ... During its losing streak, the Bull lost by five or fewer points four times. ... Despite the NBA's worst record, the Bulls already have surpassed last year's win total of 16.
